# Lib Layer Rules

This directory contains framework infrastructure shared across the app. Nothing here should have knowledge of specific containers or their business logic.

## ErrorBoundary

- Must remain a class component (React requirement for `getDerivedStateFromError`)
- Must expose `resetErrorBoundary` so `ContainerSlot` or users can trigger retry
- Must log errors with the `[ContainerError]` prefix for searchability
- Must accept optional `fallback` and `onError` props — typed, not `any`

```typescript
interface ErrorBoundaryProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  fallback?: React.ReactNode;
  onError?: (error: Error, errorInfo: React.ErrorInfo) => void;
}
```

## ContainerSkeleton

- Accepts a `shape` prop typed to `SlotShape` — must stay in sync with `ContainerSlot`
- Renders shape-appropriate loading states (tall skeleton for sidebar, wide for header, etc.)
- Must not contain any actual content or business logic

## Utils (`utils.ts`)

- `cn()` is the className merge utility (clsx + tailwind-merge)
- Keep this file minimal — only truly generic, zero-dependency helpers
- If a utility is container-specific, it belongs in that container's directory

## Tools (`tools/`)

- All tool definitions follow the AI SDK `tool()` pattern with Zod schemas
- Every tool's `execute` must validate inputs via `sandbox.ts` before any filesystem or shell operation
- Tools must never import from `src/containers/` — they are backend infrastructure
- `sandbox.ts` is the security boundary — all path validation and command blocking lives here

## Prompts (`prompts/`)

- `system.ts` generates the system prompt dynamically by reading `.claude/skills/` at runtime
- Never hard-code skill names — the generator discovers them from the filesystem
- Treat prompt changes as code changes — version and evaluate before shipping
